haracters when the setting is omitted.\n\nFor the numeric convertors (BigDecimalConvertor, IntegerConvertor, LongConvertor), the knowledge file shows \"null不許容\" as the default, and while the source just references StringConvertor for details, this is a reasonable inference since they share the same default behavior.\n\nNow I'm examining a Java code example that demonstrates how to apply custom converter annotations to property setters, specifically showing a date property with a YYYYMMDD converter annotation.\n\nLooking at the knowledge file, I notice it omits the private field declaration that appears in the source - a minor gap but not a fabrication. More significantly, the source document uses multiple h2-level sections for each class, but the knowledge file consolidates everything into a single section, which doesn't reflect the original structure. I'm realizing I need to clarify the RST heading hierarchy here. The source document uses `----` for the main title and `====` for the class sections, which makes those `====` lines equivalent to h2 headings. But the validation rule is checking for h2 headings marked with `------` (six dashes), not four. So I need to recount what's actually in the source versus what the knowledge file has split into. I see the issue now—the source has 9 class sections marked with `====`, but the knowledge file only contains 1 section. The V3 check is looking for split-level headings (h2 in RST, which would be the secondary heading structure), and there's a mismatch between what the source defines as logical sections and what's actually in the knowledge output. The source document has 9 h2 sections (marked with equals signs) all grouped into a single knowledge file section, which is a deliberate design choice for organizing related validators and converters together. The V3 validation rule checks whether the number of split-level headings matches the knowledge section count, so this 9-to-1 mapping is worth flagging as a potential misma